JOHANNESBURG About 30,000 chickens have been culled due to an outbreak of avian flu in the Western Cape.The Department of Agriculture, Fisheries and Forestry is urging people to be more vigilant.A total of 24 cases of bird flu have been reported, in Mpumalanga, Gauteng, KwaZulu-Natal and the Western Cape, including on 10 chicken farms and three ostrich farms. Avian Flu has been detected at The Duck Farm in Cape Town. The farm has been placed under quarantine and 49k ducks will be culled. #BirdFlu pic.twitter.com/7gBAgDmSw8 Small-scale poultry farmers are being hit the hardest.Thousands of birds have been culled in a bid to stop the spread of the virus.WATCH: What is bird flu and can you get it?The department said on Wednesday it was working with global partners to find solutions.Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Senzeni Zokwana said: Negotiations with international trade partners are ongoing to ensure a continuation of trade from disease-free compartments with special bio-security measures. Close on 49 000 ducks on The Duck Farm in Cape Town will be culled after Avian Influenza was detected on the farm. #BirdFlu pic.twitter.com/4coEDrESKx "The continued cooperation of the public and the poultry industry in the timeous reporting of sick and dying birds to the department of veterinary services is vital for the effectiveness of disease control and we thank the public and the poultry industry. The department stressed that no person in South Africa had contracted bird flu.Reuters